# Assignment Operators

Assignment operators assign values to variables.

## Basic Assignment

```java
int x = 10;
```

`=` assigns the value `10` to the variable `x`.

---

## Compound Assignment Operators

| Operator | Equivalent Expression |
|-----------|-----------------------|
| += | x = x + value |
| -= | x = x - value |
| *= | x = x * value |
| /= | x = x / value |
| %= | x = x % value |

---

## Example

```java
int x = 10;

x += 5;

System.out.println(x);
```

Output

```
15
```

---

# Relational Operators

Relational operators compare two values.

The result is always a boolean (`true` or `false`).

| Operator | Meaning |
|-----------|----------|
| == | Equal To |
| != | Not Equal To |
| > | Greater Than |
| < | Less Than |
| >= | Greater Than or Equal To |
| <= | Less Than or Equal To |

---

## Example

```java
int a = 10;
int b = 20;

System.out.println(a < b);
System.out.println(a == b);
System.out.println(a != b);
```

Output

```
true
false
true
```

---

# Difference Between = and ==

## =

Assignment Operator

Assigns a value to a variable.

Example

```java
int age = 22;
```

---

## ==

Comparison Operator

Checks whether two values are equal.

Example

```java
System.out.println(age == 22);
```

Output

```
true
```

---

# Logical Operators

Logical operators work with boolean values.

| Operator | Meaning |
|-----------|----------|
| && | Logical AND |
| || | Logical OR |
| ! | Logical NOT |

---

# Logical AND (&&)

Returns `true` only if **both** conditions are true.

Example

```java
int age = 25;

System.out.println(age > 18 && age < 60);
```

Output

```
true
```

---

# Logical OR (||)

Returns `true` if **at least one** condition is true.

Example

```java
System.out.println(5 > 10 || 20 > 10);
```

Output

```
true
```

---

# Logical NOT (!)

Reverses a boolean value.

Example

```java
boolean passed = true;

System.out.println(!passed);
```

Output

```
false
```

---

# Short-Circuit Evaluation

## Logical AND (&&)

If the first condition is **false**, Java does not evaluate the second condition.

Example

```java
if(false && 10 / 0 > 1)
```

The second condition is skipped.

No ArithmeticException occurs.

---

## Logical OR (||)

If the first condition is **true**, Java does not evaluate the second condition.

Example

```java
if(true || 10 / 0 > 1)
```

The second condition is skipped.

---

# Difference Between && and &

## &&

- Logical AND
- Uses short-circuit evaluation
- Stops evaluating if the first condition is false

---

## &

- Evaluates both operands
- Used as:
  - Logical AND (for boolean expressions)
  - Bitwise AND (for integer values)

---

# Difference Between || and |

## ||

- Logical OR
- Uses short-circuit evaluation
- Stops evaluating if the first condition is true

---

## |

- Evaluates both operands
- Used as:
  - Logical OR (for boolean expressions)
  - Bitwise OR (for integer values)

---

# Ternary Operator

A shorthand form of `if-else`.

Syntax

```java
condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse;
```

Example

```java
int age = 20;

String result = age >= 18 ? "Eligible" : "Not Eligible";

System.out.println(result);
```

Output

```
Eligible
```

---

# Bitwise Operators (Introduction)

Bitwise operators work on binary representations of integers.

| Operator | Meaning |
|-----------|----------|
| & | Bitwise AND |
| \| | Bitwise OR |
| ^ | Bitwise XOR |
| ~ | Bitwise NOT |
| << | Left Shift |
| >> | Right Shift |

Example

```java
System.out.println(5 & 3);
```

Binary

```
5 = 0101
3 = 0011
```

Result

```
0001
```

Output

```
1
```

